{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"Containers & Breakpoints","slug":"bootstrap-containers-breakpoints","subject":"Bootstrap","category":"Frontend Framework","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["Bootstrap Grid System"],"learning_objectives":["Fluid vs Fixed Containers","Responsive Breakpoints (sm, md, lg, xl, xxl)"],"theory":"## Responsive Control\n\n### Containers\nContainers center your content and provide padding.\n1. `.container`: Fixed width. Steps in width at each breakpoint (540px, 720px...).\n2. `.container-fluid`: Full width (100%) always.\n\n### Breakpoints\nBootstrap uses class infixes to define *when* a layout applies.\n* `xs` (None): <576px (Default, mobile)\n* `sm`: ≥576px\n* `md`: ≥768px (Tablets)\n* `lg`: ≥992px (Laptops)\n* `xl`: ≥1200px (Desktops)\n* `xxl`: ≥1400px (Big Screens)\n\n### Responsive Columns\n`col-md-6` means \"Take 6 columns (50%) on **Medium** screens and larger. On smaller screens, stack (100%)\".","syntax":".col-[breakpoint]-[number]","examples":[{"code":"<div class=\"col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4\">...</div>","output":"Phone: 100% width. Tablet: 50% width. Desktop: 33% width.","explanation":"Mobile-first stacking strategy."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using `col-xs-6`.","correction":"The `xs` infix does not exist in Bootstrap 5 classes. It is implied. Just use `.col-6`.","example":"class=\"col-xs-6\" (Wrong) -> class=\"col-6\" (Correct)."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What happens if I use `.col-6` without a breakpoint?","answer":"It applies to ALL screen sizes, from mobile up to desktop. The element will always be 50% width.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Product Grid","description":"1 item/row on phone (`col-12`), 2 items on tablet (`col-sm-6`), 4 items on desktop (`col-lg-3`).","code":"class=\"col-12 col-sm-6 col-lg-3\""}],"exam_notes":["Breakpoints work UPWARDS (min-width).","md = 768px.","lg = 992px.","container-fluid = 100% width."],